<Data Dictionary>

Element 1: Title
Field	Detail
Element Name	Title
Label	Game Title
URI	http://purl.org/dc/terms/title
Definition	The official name of the object as designated by its creator or publisher.
Data Values	Free text string
Cardinality: Mandatory	Yes
Cardinality: Repeatable	No (use alternate title as a sub-element if needed)
Comments	Sub-element: alternativeTitle may be used for localized or subtitle variants.
Example	Minecraft: Education Edition

Element 2: Creator
Field	Detail
Element Name	Creator
Label	Game Creator / Developer
URI	http://purl.org/dc/terms/creator
Definition	The individual, team, or studio primarily responsible for designing and developing the game.
Data Values	Free text string; use authorized form of name where possible (e.g., Library of Congress Name Authority File)
Cardinality: Mandatory	Yes
Cardinality: Repeatable	Yes (if multiple developers)
Comments	Distinct from Publisher. If creator and publisher are the same entity, both elements should still be filled separately.
Example	Mojang Studios

Element 3: Publisher
Field	Detail
Element Name	Publisher
Label	Publisher
URI	http://purl.org/dc/terms/publisher
Definition	The organization responsible for distributing or making the game publicly available.
Data Values	Free text string
Cardinality: Mandatory	No
Cardinality: Repeatable	Yes
Comments	In cases where the developer self-publishes, the same name as Creator may appear.
Example	Microsoft

Element 4: Description
Field	Detail
Element Name	Description
Label	Game Description
URI	http://purl.org/dc/terms/description
Definition	A concise textual summary of the game's content, core mechanics, and educational purpose.
Data Values	Free text string (recommended 50–300 words)
Cardinality: Mandatory	Yes
Cardinality: Repeatable	No
Comments	Should be written in plain language accessible to educators and non-specialist users. Avoid marketing language.
Example	Minecraft: Education Edition is a sandbox game in which students build structures, explore environments, and complete teacher-designed lessons across subjects including STEM, history, and language arts.

Element 5: Language
Field	Detail
Element Name	Language
Label	Available Language(s)
URI	http://purl.org/dc/terms/language
Definition	The language(s) in which the game's interface, text, and audio content are available.
Data Values	Controlled vocabulary — ISO 639-1 language codes
Cardinality: Mandatory	No
Cardinality: Repeatable	Yes
Comments	Use ISO 639-1 two-letter codes. Multiple values allowed when the game supports multiple languages.
Example	en, ko

Element 6: Issued Date
Field	Detail
Element Name	Issued
Label	Release Date
URI	http://purl.org/dc/terms/date

Definition	The original date on which the game was first publicly released.
Data Values	ISO 8601 date format (YYYY-MM-DD or YYYY)
Cardinality: Mandatory	No
Cardinality: Repeatable	No
Comments	If exact date is unknown, year alone (YYYY) is acceptable. Updated/re-released versions may be recorded in a sub-element: edgms:updateDate.
Example	2016-11-01

Element 7: Subject
Field	Detail
Element Name	Subject
Label	Subject Area
URI	http://purl.org/dc/terms/subject
Definition	The academic subject(s) or knowledge domain(s) that the game addresses or supports.
Data Values	Controlled vocabulary (see Appendix A)
Cardinality: Mandatory	Yes
Cardinality: Repeatable	Yes
Comments	Multiple subjects allowed. Use terms from Appendix A. If no existing term applies, use "General" or propose a new term.
If "Other" is used, a local note should be added to explain the subject area.
Example	Mathematics; Science

Element 8: Educational Level
Field	Detail
Element Name	EducationalLevel
Label	Educational Level
URI	http://edgms.org/schema/educationalLevel
Definition	The intended educational stage or grade range for which the game is designed or most appropriate.
Data Values	Controlled vocabulary (see Appendix B)
Cardinality: Mandatory	Yes
Cardinality: Repeatable	Yes
Comments	Based on IEEE LOM educationalLevel. Multiple levels allowed.
Example	Elementary School; Middle School

Element 9: Learning Objective
Field	Detail
Element Name	LearningObjective
Label	Learning Objective
URI	http://edgms.org/schema/learningObjective

Definition	A statement describing the specific knowledge, skill, or competency a learner is expected to develop through engagement with the game.
Data Values	Free text string; should follow action-verb format
Cardinality: Mandatory	No
Cardinality: Repeatable	Yes
Comments	Recommended to align with established frameworks such as Bloom's Taxonomy. Multiple objectives may be listed.
Example	Students will be able to apply basic algebraic reasoning to solve in-game puzzles.

Element 10: Genre
Field	Detail
Element Name	Genre
Label	Game Genre
URI	http://edgms.org/schema/genre
Definition	The gameplay or activity category that characterizes the primary mechanics and structure of the object.
Data Values	Controlled vocabulary (see Appendix C)
Cardinality: Mandatory	Yes
Cardinality: Repeatable	Yes
Comments	A game may belong to more than one genre
Example	Sandbox; Simulation

Element 11: Platform
Field	Detail
Element Name	Platform
Label	Platform / Device
URI	http://edgms.org/schema/platform

Definition	The hardware device, operating system, or web environment on which the object can be accessed or played.
Data Values	Controlled vocabulary (see Appendix D)
Cardinality:
Mandatory	Yes
Cardinality: Repeatable	Yes
Comments	Browser-based games should be listed as "Web Browser" rather than by OS.
Example	Windows; macOS; iPad

Element 12: Play Mode
Field	Detail
Element Name	PlayMode
Label	Play Mode
URI	http://edgms.org/schema/playMode

Definition	Describes whether the game is designed for individual play, cooperative group play, or competitive multiplayer interaction.
Data Values	Controlled vocabulary (see Appendix E)
Cardinality: Mandatory	No
Cardinality: Repeatable	Yes
Comments	"Classroom-wide" refers to games like Kahoot! where one game is shared across an entire class simultaneously.
Example	Single-player; Cooperative Multiplayer

Element 13: Educational Use Type
Field	Detail
Element Name	EducationalUseType
Label	Educational Use Type
URI	http://edgms.org/schema/educationalUseType
Definition	Indicates the educational role or category of the digital game, game-based tool, or interactive learning environment. It distinguishes between objects originally designed for education, gamified learning platforms, commercial games repurposed for educational use, and programming or creative learning environments.
Data Values	Controlled vocabulary (see Appendix F)
Cardinality: Mandatory	Yes
Cardinality: Repeatable	No
Comments	This element helps users understand how the object fits into educational use beyond its gameplay genre or subject area. If "Other" is used, a local note should explain the category.
Example	Commercial Game Repurposed for Education

Element 14: InteractivityType
Field	Detail
Element Name	InteractivityType
Label	Interactivity Type
URI	http://edgms.org/schema/interactivityType
Definition	The primary mode through which a learner interacts with the game content.
Data Values	Controlled vocabulary (see Appendix G)
Cardinality — Mandatory	No
Cardinality — Repeatable	No
Comments	“Active" = learner must perform tasks; "Expositive" = learner receives content passively; "Mixed" = combination of both.
Example	Active

Element 15: PricingModel
Field	Detail
Element Name	PricingModel
Label	Pricing Model / Access
URI	http://edgms.org/schema/pricingModel
Definition	The pricing or access model through which the game is obtained by users or institutions.
Data Values	Controlled vocabulary (see Appendix H)
Cardinality — Mandatory	No
Cardinality — Repeatable	No
Comments	"Freemium" refers to games with a free base version and paid premium features. Institutional License applies to school/district-wide licensing models.
Example	Institutional License

<Controlled Vocabulary Appendix>

Appendix A — Subject Area
(This vocabulary is recommended for values entered in dcterms:subject. Because dcterms:subject is reused from the external DCMI Terms schema, the values are documented as a local EDGMS recommendation rather than enforced directly through XSD enumeration.)
Mathematics / Science / Language Arts / Social Studies / History / Geography / Computer Science / Foreign Language / Art / Music / Physical Education / Career Education / General / Other
Appendix B — Educational Level
Early Childhood (Pre-K) / Elementary School (K-5) / Middle School (6-8) / High School (9-12) / Undergraduate / Lifelong Learning / All Ages
Appendix C — Game Genre
Puzzle / Simulation / Role-Playing Game (RPG) / Strategy / Sandbox / Quiz / Adventure / Platformer / Typing / Language Learning / Other
Appendix D — Platform
Windows / macOS / Linux / iOS / Android / Web Browser / Nintendo Switch / Other
Appendix E — Play Mode
Single-player / Cooperative Multiplayer / Competitive Multiplayer / Classroom-wide
Appendix F — Educational Use Type
Explicitly Educational Game / Gamified Learning Platform / Commercial Game Repurposed for Education / Educational Programming Environment / Gamified Learning Tool / Other
Appendix G — Interactivity Type
Active / Expositive / Mixed
Appendix H — Pricing Model
Free / Freemium / Paid (One-time) / Subscription-based / Institutional License / Open Educational Resource / Other
